  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Singer extends his 1972 argument with updated empirical evidence and practical guidance. He argues that the affluent have strong obligations to give effectively to address extreme poverty, introducing a graduated giving scale (10-33% of income based on wealth). The book bridges utilitarian theory and effective altruism practice.

  RELEVANCE: Directly relevant to the project's focus on income-based giving norms. Singer's graduated scale provides a concrete operationalization of utilitarian obligations, but raises the question of why income rather than assets should be the metric. His pragmatic accommodations to demandingness worries illustrate how maximizing consequentialism gets moderated in practice.

  POSITION: Represents moderate utilitarian consequentialism with practical accommodations. Singer maintains the core duty to maximize good but accepts graduated requirements that fall short of full sacrifice.
